Cicero, describing Verres' riotous living, says, “ iste enim praetor severus ac diligens qui populi Romani legibus nunquam paru- isset, illis legibus quae in poculis poneban- tur diligenter obtemperabat” (Act. ii. 5. 11). One of the strictest laws of a ban- quet directed by a presiding symposiarch would have reference to the regulation of the quantity of wine to be drunk by each guest at each round. Horace's notion of liberty is to drink as much or as little as he pleased‚ which is expressed by ‘inaequales calices? [‘ Acria pocula ;’ ‘ acria ' seems to mean ‘ strong‚' and ‘ modicis’ will be the opposite]

Epod. i. 7.] 75. usus rectumne] Cicero makes Laelius indignantly deny the doctrine that makes utility the foundation of friendship, and he says with much truth and delicacy, “ non enim tam utilitas parta per amicum quam amici amor ipse delectat” (Lael. e. 14). There is more in the same strain in c. 8, where he makes virtue the basis of friend- ship. Ovid (ex Pont. ii. 3. 7) says mom-n-

fully enough :—

“ Turpe quidem dictu sed (si modo vera fatemur) Vulgus amicitias utilitate probat.''
